Roostify

API and SDK Documentation

Version: 4.0.0
This site documents the REST APIs for the Roostify core platform. You can find more documentation at developer.roostify.com. For this sample, you can use the api key `special-key` to test the authorization filters.

Creating an access control group

        }
    }
}

accessControlGroups

Updating an access control group

Updates an access control group. On the URI line to call this endpoint, pass the ID for the access-control group to update (returned in the response when you created the group). You can also pass the system name instead of the ID. You can update any of the parameters for this endpoint. In the body that you pass, you can specify a different name and different system name for the group. In `account_permissions` specify the access level (`none`, `read-only`, or `full_access`) for each available resource. The permission for any resource for which you don''t provide a value defaults to `none`. This endpoint uses a `PUT` method, which means that Roostify replaces the entire resource with the values that you specify. It doesn''t simply update the fields for which you provide a value. If you omit a value for a resource, its permission defaults to `none`, even if you supplied a value when you created the group to begin with. ***PUT*** ```https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/access_control_groups/:id_or_system_name``` This call returns the names and permissions that you defined, as well as an ID for the group and the timestamp for when it was updated. 


/access_control_groups_update

import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.AccessControlApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class AccessControlApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();
        // Configure HTTP basic authorization: basicAuth
        HttpBasicAuth basicAuth = (HttpBasicAuth) defaultClient.getAuthentication("basicAuth");
        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");
        basicAuth.setPassword("YOUR PASSWORD");

        AccessControlApi apiInstance = new AccessControlApi();
        String idOrSystemName = idOrSystemName_example; // String | ID or system name of the task. If searching for an ID matching the given string  yields no results, Roostify attempts to find; the access control group by using the system name instead.
        try {
            apiInstance.accessControlGroups(idOrSystemName);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling AccessControlApi#accessControlGroups");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

accessControlWhSchema

Access control webhook schema

You can subscribe to the `resource.access_granted` webhook to be notified when a user is granted access to a resource, such as a loan. ***GET*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/your-access-control-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook ``` 


/your-access-control-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook

docOverview2

About access control groups

Creates an access control group. In the body that you pass to this endpoint, specify a name and optional system name for the group. In `account_permissions` specify the access level (`none`, `read-only`, or `full_access`) for each available resource. The permission for any resource for which you don't provide a value defaults to `none`. **POST** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/access\\_control\\_groups ``` This call returns the names and permissions that you defined, as well as an ID for the group and the timestamp for when it was created. 


/access-control-description

Accounts

aboutAccounts

About accounts

Roostify users are members of an account. Accounts manage billing, permissions, service integrations, application and workflow customizations, co-branding styles, etc. When you sign up as a client or partner with Roostify, your Roostify customer service manager (CSM) creates a Roostify account for you. You may access the basic information of any account that has an integration with your service. Use the `/accounts` resource to list or retrieve accounts. 


/accounts-description

Usage and SDK Samples

listAccounts

Listing accounts

Lists all accounts. This call requires no parameters. It identifies your service through the username token in the `Authorization` header. However, you can use the optional `page` and `count` parameters to paginate the results. ***GET*** ```https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/accounts?page=&count= Returns the ID, name, and domains for all accounts. 


/accounts

consent

Consents webhook schema

You can subscribe to the `consent.changed` webhook to be notified when a user changes his or her consent. ***GET*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/your-consent-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook ``` 


/your-consent-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook

createLead

Creating a lead

Creates a lead. Roostify allows you to convert a lead into a loan application by populating an application with details of the borrower that you gathered in the lead. Note Each parameter that you pass to this endpoint must be “whitelisted” or Roostify will not allow it. POST https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/leads 


/leads

import io.swagger.client.auth.*;
import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.DefaultApi;

import java.util.*;

public class DefaultApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();
        // Configure HTTP basic authorization: basicAuth

documentWHSchema

Documents webhook schema

You can subscribe to the following events that trigger the sending of a document webhook: `document.downloaded` Triggered when a user downloads a document from a Roostify task. `task.documentuploaded` Triggered when a user uploads a document to a Roostify task. See <a href='#create-webhook'>Creating a webhook</a> for more information. ***GET*** https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/your-documents-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook 


/your-documents-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook

updatingTask

Updates a task

Updates a task. Call this endpoint and specify a task ID with the URI to identify the task to update. In the body of the call you can update any or all of the `description`, `completed_at`, or `instructions` fields. <Note Although each of these parameters is optional, you must specify at least one of them when calling this endpoint. ***PATCH*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1//tasks/123456 ```


/tasks/{update}

DesktopUnderwriterReport

desktopUnderwriterWebhook

Desktop underwriter report webhook schema

A desktop underwriter report is a risk assessment issued by Fannie Mae. It belongs to a loan application. You can subscribe to the `du_report.success` webhook to be notified when a user successfully runs this report in Roostify. ***GET*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/your-desktop-underwriter-webhook-endpoint ``` 


/your-desktop-underwriter-webhook-endpoint

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl

        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");

            RetrievingDU result = apiInstance.desktopUnderwriterWebhook();
            System.out.println(result);

Documents

creatingDocument

Uploading a document

Uploads a document. To upload a document, you call `/documents` and pass the definition of the file in the JSON body. Note that you must associate the file to a loan application with `loan_application_id` or to a task with `task_id`. In `file_content`, pass the base64-encoded cdontent of the document. The response includes fields for the document ID (`id`) and the location from which to download the file (`api_download_path`). ***POST*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/documents ```


/documents

About documents

The ability to upload and download documents for viewing and e-signing is integral to the loan-application process. Use the `documents` resource to list, upload, retrieve, update, or download documents.

        HttpBasicAuth basicAuth = (HttpBasicAuth) defaultClient.getAuthentication("basicAuth");
        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");
        basicAuth.setPassword("YOUR PASSWORD");

        DocumentsApi apiInstance = new DocumentsApi();
        String list = list_example; // String | 
        String page = page_example; // String | The page of the index to return. If you omit this parameter but specify count, it defaults to 1. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        String count = count_example; // String | The number of records to return per page. If you omit this parameter but specify page, it defaults to 100. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        String search = search_example; // String | Terms for searching document metadata. Current searchable terms are: document_name, loan_application_reference_id, and loan_application_id.
        String filter = filter_example; // String | Term for filtering document metadata based presence of reference_id.
        try {
            array[Documents] result = apiInstance.listingDocuments(list, page, count, search, filter);
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling DocumentsApi#listingDocuments");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

/your-leads-webhook-endpoint

LoanApplicationsV1

getLoanAppFnm

Retrieving a loan application in FNM format

Returns a loan application in Fannie Mae file format (FNM). On the URI line, pass the ID of the loan application to retrieve as shown in the sample. **GET** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/loan\_applications/{id}/fnm ``` This endpoint returns a string that contains the entire loan application, converted to FNM format and Base64-encoded. 


/v1/loan_applications/{id}/fnm

getLoanMismo

Retrieving a loan application in MISMO format

Returns a loan in Mortgage Industry Standards Maintenance Organization file format (MISMO). On the URI line, pass the ID of the loan application to retrieve as shown in the sample. **GET** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/loan\_applications/{id}/mismo ``` This endpoint returns the entire content of the loan in MISMO XML format. 


/v1/loan_applications/{id}/mismo

getOrderById

Updating a loan application

Updates a loan application. On the URI line, pass the ID of the loan application to update as shown in the sample. In the body, pass parameters to add to or change the contents of the specified loan application. Note that this endpoint uses a `PATCH` method for the update, which means that it does not overwrite the entire loan application but only changes the contents for the specific fields that you specify. **PATCH** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/loan\_applications/10192837 ``` This endpoint returns the message&#58; `Loan application updated` for a successful call.

listLoanApps

Listing loan applications

Retrieves all loan applications that belong to your account or its descendants. **Note** If you don't use pagination (which is off by default), and you have a large number of loan applications, this call may time out. See [Query parameters](#pagination) to understand how to use the `count` and `page` parameters to paginate results. Use the `search` parameter to retrieve a loan application based on reference ID (`reference_id`) or loan ID (`id`) attributes. You can also use the `created`, `submitted`, and `updated` parameters to filter the list of loan applications to return based on date ranges. **GET** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1//loan\_applications?search=&page=&count=&created=2017-04-01T12:34:56Z..2017-05-01T12:34:56Z&submitted=2017-04-01T12:34:56..2017-05-01T12:34:56&updated=2017-04-01T12:34:56-08:00..2017-05-01T12:34:56-08:00 ``` ##### See also * [Creating loans](#creating-loans) to create a loan application. * [Retrieving loans](#retrieving-loans) to retrieve more details about a specific loan application. * [Retrieving a loan application in FNM format](#retrieving-loans-fnm) to retrieve details about a specific loan application in FNM format. * [Retrieving a loan application in MISMO format](#retrieving-loans-mismo) to retrieve details about a specific loan application in MISMO format.

        String submitted = submitted_example; // String | A date range that filters loan applications based on when they were submitted. Format the string as two ISO-8601 datestamps seperated by ‘…’. If you omit the time zone designator, it defaults to UTC. Example: 2017-04-01T12:34:56Z..2017-05-01T12:34:56Z

listParameters

About list parameters

List parameters are similar to regular parameters but allow you to denote multiple occurrences of the same field by incrementing the integer at the end of the field name. For example, you could specify a borrower's most recent and previous addresses as follows * `b_home1_address1` borrower's most recent address * `b_home2_address1` borrower's previous address The field prefix ( `b_home1, b_home2` ) is followed by the subfield name ( `address1` ), which does not increment. Generally, you should order fields from most recent to least recent. However, when processing a loan application, Roostify orders fields by start\\_date and end\\_date if those subfields apply. As is the case with regular parameters, list parameters begin with b\\_ or c\\_ to dentote whether they refer to the borrower or co-borrower. This documentation lists only the borrower fields, but there is an identical co-borrower field for each field that is listed. Roostify provides the following fields * `home` — Two year residential history for the borrower/co-borrower. * `employer` — Two year employment history for the borrower/co-borrower. * `assets` — List of assests to take into account for the loan application. * `income` — Non-employment income for the borrower/co-borrower. * `liabilitiy` — Liabilities for the borrower/co-borrower. * `property` — List of properties for the borrower/co-borrower. Listed below are all fields and subfields, using 1 as the occurrence number and b\\_ as the prefix. ### Home * `b_property1_address1 (string)` First address line of the property. * `b_property1_address2 (string)` Second address line of the property. * `b_property1_city (string)` City of the property. * `b_property1_state (string)` State of the property. * `b_property1_zip (string)` Zip code of the property. n * `b_property1_subject_property (boolean)` Whether the loan application is for the specified property. The default is false. Set to true if the loan is to refinance the loan on the specified property. * `b_property1_property_type (enum)` The type of property, one of `condo (string), town_home (string), single_family (string), multi_family (string), manufactured (string)`. n * `b_property1_property_use (enum)` Use of the property, one of-`primary (string), secondary (string), investment (string),`. * `b_property1_property_status (string)` Ownership status of the property, one of `residence (string), rental (string), sold (string), pending_sale (string)`. * `b_property1_title_status (string)` Title status of the property, one of-`sole (string), joint_spouse (string), joint_other (string)`. * `b_property1_market_value (integer)` Estimated market value of the property. * `b_property1_annual_tax (float)` Annual property taxes for the property. * `b_property1_monthly_homeowners_insurance (float)` Monthly homeowners insurance paid for the property. * `b_property1_monthly_hoa (float)` Monthly HOA dues paid for the property. * `b_property1_rental_income (float)` Monthly net rental income earned on the property. * `b_property1_monthly_mortgage (float)` Monthly first mortgage payment paid for the property. * `b_property1_mortgage_loan_type (enum)` Type of first mortgage for the property, one of `conventional (string), fha (string), va (string), usda (string)`. * `b_property1_mortgage_rate (float)` Interest rate of the first mortgage for the property. * `b_property1_mortgage_balance (float)` Remaining balance of the first mortgage for the property. * `b_property1_monthly_mortgage_insurance (float)` Monthly mortgage insurance paid for the property. * `b_property1_mortgage_term_remaining (integer)` Number of months left in the first mortgage term for the property. * `b_property1_second_monthly_mortgage (float)` Monthly second mortgage payment paid for the property. * `b_property1_second_mortgage_loan_type (enum)` Type of second mortgage for the property, one of `heloc (string), traditional (string)` * `b_property1_second_mortgage_rate (float)` Interest rate of the second mortgage for the property. * `b_property1_second_mortgage_balance (float)` Remaining balance of the second mortgage for the property. * `b_property1_second_mortgage_term_remaining (integer)` Number of months left in the second mortgage term for the property. \n * `b_property1_third_monthly_mortgage (float)` Monthly third mortgage payment paid for the property. * `b_property1_third_mortgage_loan_type (enum)` Type of third mortgage for the property, one of `heloc (string), traditional (string)`. * `b_property1_third_mortgage_rate (float)` Interest rate of the second mortgage for the property. * `b_property1_third_mortgage_balance (float)` Remaining balance of the third mortgage for the property. * `b_property1_third_mortgage_term_remaining (integer)` Number of months left in the third mortgage term for the property.

loanAppFindID

Retrieving a loan application

Retrieves a specific loan application. Pass a loan application ID on the URI line to identify the loan application to retrieve. ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/loan_applications/{find_id} ``` 


/v1/loan_applications/{find_id}

loanAppWebhook

Loan application webhook schema

You can subscribe to the following events that trigger the sending of a loan application webhook `loan_application.completed` Triggered when a loan application is archived in Roostify. `loan_application.created` Triggered when a loan officer manually creates a loan application for a borrower.`loan_application.econsent_changed` Triggered when a borrower agrees to e-consent.`loan_application.manual_export_request` Triggered when a loan officer manually exports a loan application from Roostify.`loan_application.started` Triggered when a borrower clicks the referral link from a loan officer and starts a loan application.`loan_application.submistted` Triggered when a loan application is submitted.`loan_application.verification_of_income_requested` Triggered when verification of borrower's income is requested 


/your-loan-application-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook

placeOrder

Creating a loan application

Creates a loan application. Creating a loan application must be granted on a service by service basis. Access is denied by default. A loan application may be created with any of the attributes listed above as parameters to the API. **POST** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1//loan\_applications ``` 


/v1/loan_applications/

                Debug.WriteLine(result);
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                Debug.Print("Exception when calling LoanApplicationsV1Api.placeOrder: " + e.Message );
            }
        }
    }
}

readLoanApp

Loan applications V1

The loan application resource is central to the Roostify system. Most other objects belong to or interact with the loan application object in some way. The loan application object consists of two types of attributes, or parameters - standard parameters and list parameters. Standard parameters include the following categories * Basic attributes — Provide basic information about the loan, the borrower/co-borrower, and the property. * Custom attributes — Attributes that you add. * HMDA attributes — Provide attributes for HMDA details. * Subject property — Provide details about the property. List parameters are similar to standard parameters but allow you to define multiple instances of the same parameter. They are organized into the following categories * Home — Specify the borrower/co-borrower's two-year residential history * Employer — Specify the borrower/co-borrower's two-year employment history * Assest — List the borrower/co-borrower's assets * Liability — List the borrower/co-borrower's liabilities. * Property — List properties that the borrower/co-borrow own or owned in the past. * Consents — Specify consents that the borrower/co-borrower have agreed to. Any field prefixed with `b` is relevant to the borrower, whereas any field prefixed with `c` is relevant to the co-borrower. For the following documentation, we will only list borrower relevant fields, though any field that has the `b` prefix can also be used for the co-borrower by replacing it with `c`. Though it is not necessary, if you would like to supply the following parameters inside a root element, you'll need to add the case sensitive name of the root object as a URL parameter, e.g. “root=Contact”. Additionally, if you would like to override the body of the response in the event of a successful request, in the case of an exporting system that requires a known static response such as “success”, you can supply an additional URL parameter called “success” with the text you are expecting, e.g. “success=1"

Parameters

Query parameters
Name Description
name
String
Name of the loan application, visible only to the loan officer
reference_id
String
Arbitrary reference string for an originating service (you).
fnm
String
The Base64-encoded string of the entire loan application. Roostify first parses the values from the FNM file, then applies values from any attributes that you set, which allows you to overwrite the FNM file with custom values.
agent_email
String
Email of the borrower’s real estate agent.
send_email
Boolean
Whether to create a borrower user and send them an email invitation with the link to the generated application.
send_invite
Boolean
Whether Roostify should send an email invitation to the borrower with the link to the generated loan application. Set to false if you are planning to send the URL for the loan application to the borrower yourself.
lender_email
String
Email address of the loan officer to whom the loan application should be assigned. If empty, the loan application will automatically be assigned according to the account settings (usually an account administrator).
sso_reference_id
String
SSO (Single Sign On) reference ID of the loan officer to whom the loan application should be assigned. If empty, the loan application will automatically be assigned according to the account settings (usually an account administrator).
b_email
String
The email address of the borrower.
borrower_sso_reference_id
String
Borrower SSO (Single Sign On) reference ID of the borrower of the loan application. When provided with b_email a borrower is created as well. This allows the borrower to Single Sign On to complete the rest of their loan application. Must include b_email with the request parameter.

creatingALoanApplication

Creating a Loan Application

Creating a Loan Application must be granted on a service by service basis. Access is denied by default. **A Loan Application may be created with any of the attributes listed above as parameters to the API.**

namespace Example
{
    public class creatingALoanApplicationExample
    {
        public void main()
        {
            // Configure HTTP basic authorization: basicAuth
            Configuration.Default.Username = "YOUR_USERNAME";
            Configuration.Default.Password = "YOUR_PASSWORD";

            var apiInstance = new LoanApplicationsV2Api();
            var body = new CreatingaLoanApplicationrequest(); // CreatingaLoanApplicationrequest | 

            try
            {
                // Creating a Loan Application
                CreatingaLoanApplicationresponse result = apiInstance.creatingALoanApplication(body);
                Debug.WriteLine(result);
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                Debug.Print("Exception when calling LoanApplicationsV2Api.creatingALoanApplication: " + e.Message );
            }
        }
    }
}

listingYourLoanApplications

Listing your Loan Applications

This will retrieve all loan applications belonging to your account or its descendants. For clients with many loan applications, this may time out if you do not use pagination. By default, we do not paginate results. **Overview** Use the applicants array to provide details about the borrowers. You can specify up to four borrowers. ``` { ... "applicants": [ { "id": "356249128" "user_id": "265489137" "personal": {"..."}, "residence": {"..."}, "properties": ["..."], "asset_details": {"..."}, "employment_details": {"..."}, "veteran_details": {"..."}, "liability_details": {"..."}, "credit": {"..."}, "downpayment_additional_source": {"..."}, "hmda": {"..."}, "primary_borrower": true, "econsent": {"..."}, "consent": {"..."} } ... ] } ``` **Borrower Info** For each applicant, use the following fields to provide unique IDs and to specify whether the borrower is the primary borrower for the loan + **id** (string) — A unique ID for the borrower for this loan application. If the borrower applies for another loan, assign her or him a different ID for that application. + **user_id** (string) — A unique ID for the borrower in Roostify. + **primary_borrower** (Boolean) — Whether borrower is the primary borrower. You must designate one, and only one borrower as the primary borrower. ``` "applicants": [ { "id": "795641238", "user_id": "985674231", "primary_borrower": "true" ... }, { "id": "579864213", "user_id": "659183724", "primary_borrower": "false" ... } ] ``` **Personal** The personal object specifies personal details for the borrower. Below sample shows personal details for one borrower. + ssn (string, optional) — Borrower’s social security number. + dob (date, optional) — Borrower’s date of birth. + email (string, required) — Borrower’s email address. + first_name (string, optional) — Borrower’s first name. + last_name (string, optional) — Borrower’s last name. + phone (string, optional) — Borrower’s phone number. + years_schooling (integer, optional) — Number of years of schooling for the borrower. + dependents (integer, optional) — Comma separated list of dependents listed by age in years. For example, to specify two dependents, ages 5 and 15 5,15. + marital (object, optional) — Borrower’s marital information. + marital_status (enum, optional) — Unmarried = 1; Married = 2; Separated = 3. + married_with (string, optional) — Full Name of an applicant to whom the borrower is married if they're on the loan + joint_with (string, optional) — Full Name of the applicant with whom this applicant is joint with. + residence (array) — Current mailing address and two-year listing of borrower’s physical residence. See Residence for details. ``` "personal": { "ssn": "111111111", "dob": "10/05/1991", "email": "john111@gmail.com", "first_name": "John", "last_name": "Schuler", "phone": "9562528908", "years_schooling": "16", "dependents": "5,15", "marital": { "marital_status": 2, "married_with": "Jane Schuler" }, "joint_with":"Jane Schuler", "residence": { "mailing_address": { "address1": "PO Box 147", "city": "Chester", "state": "CA", "zip": "96020" }, "home_address": [ { "address1": "1 Main Street", "address2": "Apt D", "city": "Chester", "state": "CA", "zip": "96020", "months": null, "own": false, "start_date": "11/01/2017" }, { "address1": "2 Main Street", "address2": "Apt C", "city": "Regal", "state": "AL", "zip": "54321", "months": 6, "own": false, "start_date": "03/01/2016" } ] } } ``` **Residence** The residence object enables you to specify the current mailing address and two-year listing of the borrower’s physical residence. It is part of the personal object that enables you to specify personal and residential information for up to four borrowers. The residence object contains two structures: + mailing_address (object, optional) — Details of the mailing address. + address1: (string, optional) — Address line one of the mailing address. + address2: (string, optional) — Address line two of the mailing address. + city: (string, optional) — City of the mailing address. + state: (string, optional) — State of the mailing address. + zip: (string, optional) — Zip code of the mailing address. + home_address (array) — An array of details for each place that the borrower has lived in the past two years. + address1: (string, optional) — Address line one of the residence. + address2: (string, optional) — Address line two of the residence. + city: (string, optional) — City of the residence. + state: (string, optional) — State of the residence. + zip: (string, optional) — Zip code of the residence. + own: (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower has owned or currently owns the home. + start_date: (date, optional) — Date at which borrower started living at this address. Note that you need to specify the start date only. There is no field for the end date. + monthly_rent (integer, optional) - Amount of rent in USD. ``` "residence": { "mailing_address": { "address1": "1 Main Street", "address2": "Apt D", "city": "Regal", "state": "CA", "zip": "96119" }, "home_address": [ { "address1": "1 Main Street", "address2": "Apt D", "city": "Regal", "state": "CA", "zip": "96119", "own": false, "start_date": "11/01/2017" }, { "address1": "2 Main Street", "address2": "Apt C", "city": "Regal", "state": "AL", "zip": "54321", "months": 6, "own": false, "start_date": "03/01/2016" } ] } ``` **Properties** Use the properties array to provide details for each property that the borrower owns. + address1 (string) — First address line of the property. + address2 (string) — Second address line of the property. + city (string) — City of the property. + state (string) — State of the property. + zip (string) — Zip code for the property. + months (string) — Number of months that borrower has owned property. + own (boolean) — Whether borrower owns the property. + no_of_units (string) — Number of units. + rental_income (float) — Monthly net rental income earned on the property. + monthly_hoa (float) — Monthly HOA dues paid for the property. + monthly_mortgage (float) — Monthly mortgage payment for the property. + mortgage_rate (float) — Interest rate of the first mortgage for the property. + mortgage_balance (float) — Remaining balance of the first mortgage for the property. + monthly_mortgage (float) — Monthly mortgage payment for the property. + property_type (string) — The type of property, one of condo = 1; town_home = 2; single_family = 3; multi_family = 4; manufactured = 5. + purchase_price (string) — The purchase price. + property_use (string) — Use of the property, one of:1 = primary; 2 = secondary; 3= investment. + property_status (string) — Ownership status of the property, one of 1 = residence; 2 = rental; 3 = sold; 4 = pending_sale. + title_status (string) — Title status of the property. One of sole = 1; joint_spouse = 2; joint_other = 3., + market_value (integer) — Estimated market value of the property. + monthly_homeowners_insurance (float) — Monthly homeowner's insurance for the property. + monthly_mortgage_insurance (float) — Monthly mortgage insurance for the property. + annual_tax (float) — Annual property taxes for the property. + county_fips (string) — County FIPS code for the property. ``` "properties": [ { "address1": "1290 Tatooine Pl", "address2": "", "city": "Milan", "state": "MN", "zip": "56262", "months": null, "own": true, "no_of_units": "1", "rental_income": "1,234", "monthly_hoa": "11", "property_type": "2", "purchase_price": null, "property_use": "2", "property_status": "2", "title_status": "2", "market_value": "300,000", "monthly_homeowners_insurance": "100", "monthly_mortgage_insurance": "", "annual_tax": "1,500", "county_fips": "005" } { "address1": "115 Pacer Pl", "address2": "", "city": "Moosehead", "state": "MN", "zip": "56562" } ] ``` **Assets** Use asset_details to list the financial assets to take into account as part of the loan application. The schema for this structure is as follows + current_ownership (boolean) — Whether borrower currently owns the asset. + assets (array)— An array of one or more assets + source (string) — Source of the asset, usually an institution name, for example, 'Chase bank'. + source_type (enum) — Type of the asset, one of checking, savings, retirement, investment, other. + amount (float) — Current value of the the asset in USD. + income (array) — An array of non-employment incomes for the borrower. + amount (integer, optional) — Borrower's monthly income in USD. + source (string, optional) — The type, or source, for the income. ``` "asset_details": { "current_ownership": true, "assets": [ { "source": "Chase bank", "source_type": "checking", "amount": "50,000" } ], "incomes": [ { "source": "trust", "amount": "3,000" }, { "source": "military_flight_pay", "amount": "5,446" } ] } ``` **Declarations** Use declarations to list obligations and financial history for each borrower and also identify whether the borrower is a US citizen. + ongoing_payments (string, optional) — The type of ongoing payments that the borrower must make. One or more of (separated by commas): 1 = Alimony; 2 = child_support; 3 = no_payment. + has_ongoing_payments_exp (string, optional) — Explanation of ongoing divorce, or separation-related payments. + quarter_ownership (boolean, optional)— Whether borrower owns at least 25% of a company. + citizen (boolean, optional)— Whether borrower is a US Citizen. + alien (boolean, optional)— Whether borrower is not a US Citizen. Note that a person who is a permanent, or non-permanent, resident alien is able to purchase property in the US. Specify such a resident alien as citizen: false; alien: true. + note_debt (boolean, optional — Whether borrower is a co-maker or endorser on a note. + has_judgements (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower has outstanding judgements. + has_judgements_exp (string, optional) — Explanation of judgement. + has_bankruptcy (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is currently or has been bankrupt. + has_judgements (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower has outstanding judgements. + has_judgements_exp (string, optional) — Explanation of judgement. + has_bankruptcy (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is currently or has been bankrupt. + has_bankruptcy_exp (string, optional) — Explanation of bankruptcy. Limit of 90 characters. + has_property_foreclosure (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower’s property has been foreclosed. + has_property_foreclosure_exp (string, optional) — Explanation for foreclosure. Limit of 90 characters. + has_loan_foreclosure (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower has loan that has been foreclosed. + has_loan_foreclosure_exp (string, optional) — Explanation for foreclosure. Limit of 90 characters. + has_lawsuit (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is currently a part of a lawsuit. + has_lawsuit_exp (string, optional) — Explanation for lawsuit. Limit of 90 characters. + has_default (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower currently has loan or debt default. + has_default_exp (string, optional) — Explanation for loan or debt default. Limit of 90 characters. ``` "declarations": { "ongoing_payments": "2", "citizen": "false", "alien": "false" } ``` **Employment details** Use employment_details to provide information about the borrower's employment history for the past two years + recently_employed (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is currently employed or has been employed at some point in the last 2 years. + self_employment (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower’s current status is self employed. + employment (array, optional) — Details for one or more employers for whom the borrower has worked in the past two years. **Employment** The employment array enables you to specify employment details for the borrower for one or more employers. You should enter details for all employers for the past two years. Leave end_date empty for current employers. You may list multiple current employers if relevant. name (string) — Name of the employer. + self_employed (boolean) — Whether borrower is self-employed. + independent_contractor (boolean) — Whether borrower is an independent contractor. + years (string) — Number of years (rounded down) that the borrower has been with this employer (as alternative to start_date/end_date). + months (string) — Number of months (remaining after years) that the borrower has been with this employer (as alternative to start_date/end_date). + start_date (date) — Start date of employment (as alternative to years/months). + end_date (date) — End date of employment (as alternative to years/months). + position (string) — Borrower’s title at their employer. + business_type (string) — Name of the employer's industry. + years_in_industry (string) — Number of years (rounded down) that the borrower has been in this line of work.. + months_in_industry (string) — Number of months (remaining after years) that the borrower has been in this line of work. + phone (string) — Primary phone number of the employer. + address1 (string) — Address line 1 of the employer. + address2 (string) — Address line 2 of the employer. + city (string) — City of the employer. + state (string)— State of the employer + zip (string) — Zip code of the employer. + current (boolean) — Whether borrower is currently employed by this employer. + salary (float) — Monthly salary. + annual_salary (integer) — Annual salary. + annual_bonuses (integer) — Annual bonuses. + annual_commissions (integer) — Annual commissions. + hourly_rate (number) — Hourly rate. + regular_hours_per_week (number) — Regular hours per week. + overtime_hours_per_week (number) — Overtime hours per week. ``` "employment_details": { "employment": [ { "name": "AGF&D. Ltd", "self_employed": "false", "independent_contractor": "false", "start_date": "11/1/2017", "position": "IT Manager", "business_type": "IT Services/Software", "years_in_industry": "6", "phone": "6282528908", "address1": "4 Yavin Ct", "city": "Yavin", "state": "CA", "zip": "96112", "annual_salary": "100,000", "salary": "8,333.33", "payment_type": "salary", "annual_bonuses": "23,234", "annual_commissions": "4,000" }, { "name": "AOL Inc.", "self_employed": "false", "independent_contractor": "", "start_date": "2/1/2016", "end_date": "11/1/2017", "position": "IT technician", "business_type": "IT Services/Software", "years_in_industry": "2", "phone": "4082168844", "address1": "1 Dantooine Pl", "city": "Dantooine", "state": "CA", "zip": "96109", "payment_type": "salary" } ] } ``` **Veteran Details** Use veteran_details to specify military service and VA information for the borrower. + military_status (enum, optional) — Borrower’s military status. One of: active , retired. + military_branch (enum, optional) — Borrower’s military branch. One of: air_force, army, coast_guard, marines, navy, other. + military_service (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is now, or ever has been, a member of the Armed Forces. + military_type (enum, optional) — Borrower’s military type. One of: regular, reserves, national_guard (string) + discharged_at (datetime, optional) — When borrower was discharged from the Armed Forces. + first_va_loan (boolean, optional) — Whether this is the borrower’s first loan with the VA. + va_coe (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower has a certificate of eligibility to qualify for a VA-backed loan. + va_funding_fee_exempt (string, optional) — Whether the borrower is exempt from the VA funding fee. + va_ros (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower has a report of separation ( such as form DD-214) from the Armed Forces. ``` "veteran_details": { "military_status": "retired", "military_branch": "coast_guard", "military_service": "true", "military_type": "regular", "va_coe": "true", "first_va_loan": "true" } ``` **Liabilities** Use liability_details to list financial liabilities for the borrower, including child-support payments, as well as credit cards, auto loans, mortgages, etc. + child_support_amount (integer) — Amount of monthly child support payment. + liabilities (array) — A list financial liabilities for the borrower, including credit cards, auto loans, mortgages, etc. + type (string) — The type of liability. + creditor_name (string) — Name of the creditor. + creditor_street_address (string) — Address of creditor. + creditor_city (string) — City of creditor. + creditor_state (string) — State of creditor. + creditor_zip (string) — Zip code of creditor. + creditor_zip_four (string) — 4-digit zip suffix of creditor. + creditor_account_no (string) — Creditor account number. + monthly_amount (float) — Monthly required payment to creditor. + no_of_months_left (integer) — Number of months remaining until repayment is complete. ``` "liability_details": { "child_support_amount": "2,000", "liabilities":[ { "type":"Auto lease", "monthly_amount":325, "no_of_months_left":8 } ] } ``` **Credit** Use credit to show borrower's credit details. + estimated_credit (string, optional) — Borrower's estimate of their credit score. + allow_credit_at (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower has granted authorization to pull credit. + credit_authorized_by (string, optional) — Who granted authorization to pull credit. ``` "credit": { "estimated_credit": "excellent" } ``` **Down Payment** Use downpayment_additional_source to specify details if the down payment is coming from a source other than current assets. + down_payment_borrowed (boolean) — Whether down payment is borrowed. + down_payment_borrowed_exp (string) — Explanation of why borrower is borrowing money to make the down payment. + note_debt (boolean) — Whether borrower has a note debt for the down payment. + note_debt_exp (string) — Explanation of why borrower is using a note to make the down payment. ``` "downpayment_additional_source": { "note_debt": "true", "note_debt_exp": "Cash crunch until selling bonds." } ``` **HMDA** Use hmda to provide gender and ethnicity information per the Home Mortgage Disclosure Act (HMDA). + wants_monitoring (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower consents to government information monitoring. + hmda_provides_gender (boolean, optional) — Whether to provide gender details. + hmda_male (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is male. + hmda_female (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is female. + hmda_provides_ethnicity (boolean, optional) — Whether to provide ethnicity details. + hmda_hispanic_or_latino (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Hispanic or Latino. + hmda_not_hispanic_or_latino (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is not Hispanic or Latino.. + hmda_mexican (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Mexican. + hmda_puerto_rican (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Puerto Rican. + hmda_cuban (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Cuban. + hmda_other_hispanic_or_latino (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Hispanic or Latino other than Mexican, Cuban, or Puerto Rican. + hmda_provides_race (boolean, optional) — Whether to provide information about race. + hmda_american_indian_or_alaskan (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is American Indian or Native Alaskan. + hmda_asian (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Asian. + hmda_asian_indian (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Asian Indian. + hmda_chinese (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Chinese. + hmda_filipino (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Filipino. + hmda_japanese (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Japanese. + hmda_korean (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Korean. + hmda_vietnamese (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Vietnamese. + hmda_other_asian (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Asian other than the listed categories. + hmda_black_or_african_american (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Black or African-American. + hmda_hawaiian_or_other_pacific_islander (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Hawaiian or other Pacific Islander. + hmda_native_hawaiian (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Native Hawaiian. + hmda_guamanian_or_chamorro (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Guamanian or Chamorro. + hmda_samoan (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is Samoan. + hmda_other_pacific_islander (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is a Pacific Islander other than the listed categories. + hmda_white (boolean, optional) — Whether borrower is White. + hmda_lender_provided_gender_visually (boolean, optional) — Whether to provide gender information through visual observation. + hmda_lender_provided_race_visually (boolean, optional) — Whether to provide information about race through visual observation. + hmda_lender_provided_ethnicity_visually (boolean, optional) — Whether to provide ethnicity information through visual observation. + hmda_provides_gender (boolean, optional) — Whether to provide information about gender. + hmda_hispanic_or_latino_description (string, optional) — Description for Hispanic / Latino field. + hmda_american_indian_or_alaskan_description (string, optional) — Description for American Indian / Alaskan field. + hmda_other_asian_description (string, optional) — Description for Other Asian field. + hmda_other_pacific_islander_description (string, optional) — Description for Other Pacific Islander field. + hispanic (boolean, optional) — Discontinued — use hmda_ fields instead. + native (boolean, optional) — Discontinued — use hmda_ fields instead. + asian (boolean, optional) — Discontinued — use hmda_ fields instead. + black (boolean, optional) — Discontinued — use hmda_ fields instead. + islander (boolean, optional) — Discontinued — use hmda_ fields instead. + white (boolean, optional) — Discontinued — use hmda_ fields instead. + gender (enum, optional) — Discontinued — use hmda_ fields instead. ``` "hmda": { "hmda_male": true, "hmda_not_hispanic_or_latino": true, "hmda_american_indian_or_alaskan": true } ``` **E-consent** Use econsent to specify e-consent details for the borrower for the loan application. + econsent_status (boolean) — Whether borrower has agreed to e-consent for the loan. + econsented_at (datetime) — Date and time at which borrower agreed to e-consent in ISO 8601 date-time format. + econsented_by (string) — Name of borrower who agreed to e-consent. Note that the name is fetched from user table not from applicant table. + reference_id (string) — Arbitrary reference ID for the e-consent.

messageWebhookSchema

Schema of a message webhook

Messages allow users to instantly communicate in Roostify over a loan application. Any lenders or borrowers that are party to the loan application are notified about the message immediately. The draft version of Messages API call has been deprecated and will be removed shortly. ***GET*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/your-message-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook ``` 


/your-message-webhook-endpoint-defined-in-the-webhook

Creates a message. Note When the account’s email and name are filled in, the from address for messages created from this endpoint will use the account name and email address. Otherwise, emails will be sent from an email address similar to `no-reply@deliver.roostify.com` ***POST*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/messages ```

productOfferings

Sending UserDetails fields and values

This API Resource is currently a draft design, and while it functions, expect the schema and possibly locations of objects to change without warning. This is an object representing product offerings. You can get the product offering available to the user by posting user attributes. User attributes will be passed to appropriate backend product and pricing engine and get a list of available product terms for that user. ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/draft/offerings ```

ReferenceIDs

referenceId

Creating or updating a reference ID

Creates or updates a reference ID. You can use this endpoint to either create a reference ID or update an existing ID. PUT ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/loan_applications/reference/ ``` This call returns the reference ID, the name of the external service, the associated loan application ID, and the timestamp of when it created or updated the reference ID. 


/loan_applications/reference

referenceIdAbout

About Reference IDs

Reference IDs allow you to link an item or person in Roostify to an item or person in an external system. For example, you could use a reference ID to link a Roostify loan application to a loan application in an external system. Use the `loan_applications/reference` resource to create or update a reference ID. 


/loan_applications/reference-description

Service

retriveService

Retrieving your service

Retrieves your service.This call requires no parameters. It identifies your service through the username token in the `Authorization` header. ***GET*** `` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/service ``` This call returns the name and ID of the service, and the resources to which you have access. 


/service

service

About services

A service represents your developer account and as such, provides access to the API. Contact your CSM representative to set up a service for you. The `/service` resource provides an endpoint to retrieve information about your service. 


/service-description

Settings

integrationSettings

About integration settings

Users can customize Roostify services on an account level through the user interface. You can access these customizations through the `/settings` resource. For instance, if Roostify leverages an integration that requires configurations, you can retrieve the fields, values, and the associated lender on the account through the `retrieve-int-settings` `/settings` resource. 


/settings-description

retrieveSettings

Retrieving integration settings

Retrieves integration settings. This call requires no parameters. ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/settings ``` Returns service settings and configurations in key/value pairs as shown in the sample response. The response includes the client ID, client secret, and redirect URL, as well as details for each lender. '

StatusUpdate

createStatusUpdate

Creating a status update

Creates a status update. In the body that you pass to this call, specify the loan application ID and the content of the message. A status update appears in the stream that collaborators use to monitor updates to a loan application. 


/status_updates

Tasks

creatingTask

Creating a task

Creates a task. This call requires no URI parameters. In the body, you specify parameters to define the task, including the task name and application to associate it to (which are both required), as well as options for when it's due, instructions to complete, etc. By default, any user may work on a loan, however, you can use `assigned_role` to assign the task specifically to a lender, borrower, co-borrower, or borrower agent. This call enables you to create different types of tasks. The first sample shows a form task. Following that are samples for an approve task and a view-only task. ***POST*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/tasks ``` 


/tasks

listingTasks

Listing tasks

Lists all the tasks associated with a specific loan. When you call this endpoint, pass the ID of a loan application `loan_application_id` as a parameter with the URI. You can also specify the `page` and `count` pagination parameters to paginate the results. ***GET*** ```https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/tasks?loan_application_id=123456&page=&count= ``` 


/tasks

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl
  • Python
curl -X GET -H "Authorization: Basic [[basicHash]]" "https://roostify-gallus-qa.herokuapp.com/api/v1/tasks?loan_application_id=&page=&count="
import io.swagger.client.*;
import io.swagger.client.auth.*;
import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.TasksApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class TasksApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();
        // Configure HTTP basic authorization: basicAuth
        HttpBasicAuth basicAuth = (HttpBasicAuth) defaultClient.getAuthentication("basicAuth");
        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");
        basicAuth.setPassword("YOUR PASSWORD");

        TasksApi apiInstance = new TasksApi();
        String loanApplicationId = loanApplicationId_example; // String | A loan application ID to search for all the tasks associated with the loan.
        String page = page_example; // String | The page of the index to return. If you omit this parameter but specify count, it defaults to 1. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        String count = count_example; // String | The number of records to return per page. If you omit this parameter but specify page, it defaults to 100. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        try {
            array[ListTasks] result = apiInstance.listingTasks(loanApplicationId, page, count);
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling TasksApi#listingTasks");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

        String page = page_example; // String | The page of the index to return. If you omit this parameter but specify count, it defaults to 1. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        String count = count_example; // String | The number of records to return per page. If you omit this parameter but specify page, it defaults to 100. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        try {
            array[ListTasks] result = apiInstance.listingTasks(loanApplicationId, page, count);

schemaTaskWebhook

About tasks

You use tasks to order the work that must be done after a loan officer submits and reviews a loan application. When you create a task, you associate it to a specific loan application. Tasks range from signing financial disclosure documents to uploading a driver’s license. Roostify enables you to create the following types of tasks&#58; **Form task** A task that includes a form for the assigned user to fill out. **Approval task** A task that requires the user to sign off. **View-only task** A task that does not allow the borrower or lender to append due dates or file attachments. **Note** When you use the API to create a task, you can add due dates and append file attachments. When you create or update a task, you may assign a role to it, in which case only a user in that role may work on or complete the task. If you don’t assign a role to a task, any user may work on it. Roostify provides endpoints for the `/tasks` resource that enable you to&#58; * Create a task. * List tasks. * Retrieve a task. * Update a task. There is no webhook, per se, to use for notification of task completion. However you can create a webhook to notify your service when the outcome of a task occurs. For example, if you create a task that requires a user to upload a document, you can create a webhook that is triggered when someone uploads a document (by specifying the `event_type` as `task.document_uploaded`for the webhook that you create). 


/task-description

UserManagement

aboutUserMgmt

About user management

The API allows you to create and manage users on both the lender and borrower side. When you create a user, you assign a role, either lender or borrower (borrower, co-borrower, or borrower agent) that determines globally the resources, including loan application fields, to which the user has access. In addition, you can add a user to an <a href='#about-access-control'>access control group</a> to fine tune access to specific resources. Once a user no longer requires global access to Roostify, rather than delete them from the system, you can <a href='#deactivating-users'>deactivate</a> them. At any point you can <a href='#activating-users'>reactivate</a> the user to restore their access. The `/users` resource enables you to: <a href='#creating-users'>Create users <a href='#listing-users'>List users <a href='#retrieving-users'>Retrieve users <a href='#updating-users'>Update users <a href='#activating-users'>Activate users <a href='#deactivating-users'>Deactivate users 


/users-attributes

activatingUsers

Activating a user

Activates a user. Call this endpoint and pass the ID of a user who has been previously deactivated. ***POST*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/users/{id}/unlock ``` A successful call returns a success message but no content. to deactivate a user. 


/users/{id}/unlock

import io.swagger.client.api.UserManagementApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class UserManagementApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();
        // Configure HTTP basic authorization: basicAuth
        HttpBasicAuth basicAuth = (HttpBasicAuth) defaultClient.getAuthentication("basicAuth");
        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");
        basicAuth.setPassword("YOUR PASSWORD");

        UserManagementApi apiInstance = new UserManagementApi();
        String id = id_example; // String | Required. User’s ID.
        try {
            apiInstance.activatingUsers(id);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling UserManagementApi#activatingUsers");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

    console.log('API called successfully.');
  }
};

    {

            Configuration.Default.Password = "YOUR_PASSWORD";

            {

createUser

Creating users

Creates a user. In the body of the call, you pass parameters to: Identify the user (`first_name`, `last_name`, `email`), etc. Specify a role for the user (`user_role`), either a borrower (co-borrower, borrower agent) or lender.Optionally, add the user to an <a href='#about-access-control'>access control group</a> to assign permissions. ***POST*** https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/users This call returns an ID for the new user and the timestamp of when it created the user. <h5>See also</h5> <a href='#listing-users'>Listing users</a> to retrieve a list of all users.<a href='#retrieving-users'>Retrieving users</a> to retrieve information for a specific user. <a href='#deactivating-users'>Deactivating users</a> to deactivate a user. <a href='#about-access-control'>About access control groups</a> for information about how to use access control groups to control access to resources. 


/users

deactivatingUsers

Deactivating a user

Deactivates a user. Call this endpoint and pass the ID of the user to deactivate. A successful call returns a success message but no content.


/users/{id}/lock

import io.swagger.client.*;
import io.swagger.client.auth.*;
import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.UserManagementApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class UserManagementApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();
        // Configure HTTP basic authorization: basicAuth
        HttpBasicAuth basicAuth = (HttpBasicAuth) defaultClient.getAuthentication("basicAuth");
        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");
        basicAuth.setPassword("YOUR PASSWORD");

        UserManagementApi apiInstance = new UserManagementApi();
        String search = search_example; // String | Only lists users who match the given attributes. Param structure is search[attribute]=... It takes a URL-encoded hash of search parameters. reference_id (string, optional) - Only list users whose reference ID matches the provided reference ID.
        String page = page_example; // String | The page of the index to return. If you omit this parameter but specify count, it defaults to 1. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        String count = count_example; // String | The number of records to return per page. If you omit this parameter but specify page, it defaults to 100. If you omit both parameters, pagination is disabled.
        try {
            map['String', 'Integer'] result = apiInstance.userMgmtList(search, page, count);
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling UserManagementApi#userMgmtList");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

UserSettings

listingUserSettings

Retrieving a user's settings

Retrieves a user's settings. Call this endpoint and pass the ID of a user on the URI line to retrieve settings for a specific user. Note Retrieving settings for a particular user also returns the account settings for the account to which they belong. This reduces complexity by allowing you to make a single request for all of a particular user's settings. ***GET*** ``` https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/services/users/12356 ``` 


/services/users/{id}

WebhookEvents

listingWebhookEvents

Listing your webhook events

Lists all webhook events. Webhook events record every instance in which a webhook was fired for a particular event, and can act as an audit log for all events that occur that are trackable via webhooks. ***GET*** https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/webhook_events?created=2015-10-21T00:00:01-07:00..2016-10-21T00:00:00-07:00&page=&count= This call returns an ID for the event, the webhook ID, and the times at which the event attempts 


/webhook_events

Webhooks

aboutWebhooks

About webhooks

You can set up webhooks to alert your application of events that occur in the Roostify system. Webhooks are HTTP callbacks that receive notifications for events. To use webhooks, you set up a webhook listener, after which you can create webhooks to subscribe to specific events. When a subscribed event occurs, Roostify sends a webhook (as a `POST` request) to the listener URL that you specified. The webhook contains the event type that prompted the webhook call and the record of the object that was updated. The fields for the record that Roostify sends in the body of the `POST` request vary depending on the type of record with which the webhook is associated. **Note** Roostify does not pass any sensitive data in a webhook. Use the `/webhooks` resource to [create](#create-webhook), [list](#list-webhook), [retrieve](#retrieve-webhook), and [delete](#delete-webhook) webhooks. The Roostify API tutorial provides specific information about how to set up webhooks to track events in Roostify. 


/webhooks-description

Creating a webhook

You create a webhook by passing two body parameters to `/webhooks` `url` The URL to which Roostify sends the webhook `POST` request. `event_type` The type of event that triggers sending the webhook. ***Example*** URI POST https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/webhooks

listWebhooks

Listing webhooks

Lists all webhooks. This call requires no parameters. It identifies your service through the username token in the `Authorization` header. However, you can use the optional `page` and `count` parameters to <a href=''#pagination''>paginate</a> the results. Use `/webhooks` and pass the ID of a specific webhook to <a href=''#retrieve-webhook''> retrieve that webhook. ***Example*** URI GET</b> https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/webhooks?page=&count= ' 


/webhooks

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl
  • Python
curl -X GET -H "Authorization: Basic [[basicHash]]" "https://roostify-gallus-qa.herokuapp.com/api/v1/webhooks?page=&count="
import io.swagger.client.*;
import io.swagger.client.auth.*;
import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.WebhooksApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class WebhooksApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();
        // Configure HTTP basic authorization: basicAuth
        HttpBasicAuth basicAuth = (HttpBasicAuth) defaultClient.getAuthentication("basicAuth");
        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");
        basicAuth.setPassword("YOUR PASSWORD");

        WebhooksApi apiInstance = new WebhooksApi();
        String page = page_example; // String | The page of the index to return. If you omit this parameter but
specify count, it defaults to 1. If you omit both parameters, pagination
is disabled.

        String count = count_example; // String | The number of records to return per page. If you omit this parameter
but specify page, it defaults to 100. If you omit both parameters, pagination
is disabled.

        try {
            apiInstance.listWebhooks(page, count);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling WebhooksApi#listWebhooks");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

retrievingWebhook

Retrieving a webhook

Retrieves a specific webhook. For the inline parameter, `find_id` pass the ID of a wewbhook that has been created. Use `/webhooks` without specifying a webhook ID to '#list-webhooks' to list all webhooks. ***GET*** ```https://sandbox.roostify.com/api/v1/webhooks/{find_id}```


/webhooks/{find_id}

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl
  • Python

        HttpBasicAuth basicAuth = (HttpBasicAuth) defaultClient.getAuthentication("basicAuth");
        basicAuth.setUsername("YOUR USERNAME");
        basicAuth.setPassword("YOUR PASSWORD");

        WebhooksApi apiInstance = new WebhooksApi();
        String findId = findId_example; // String | ID of the webhook to retrieve.
        try {
            ListWebhooks result = apiInstance.retrievingWebhook(findId);
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling WebhooksApi#retrievingWebhook");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

        } catch (ApiException e) {

            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

valWebhooks

Validating webhooks

Each webhook contains the headers **X-Roostify-Extended-Signature** and **X-Roostify-Signature-Algorithm**, which you can use to verify that the webhook originated from Roostify. **X-Roostify-Signature-Algorithm** shows the algorithm that was used to generate the signature (should be ‘\ HMAC-SHA512’). **X-Roostify-Extended-Signature** contains a signature that is created by calculating the HMAC-SHA512 hex-encoded digest of your service’s access token and the webhook's request body. The following examples demonstrate how to validate the signature in Ruby and C#, respectively, by implementing a `verify_signature` method that compares the provided signature against a token generated by `create_token`. You pass a message and secret to `create_token`, which hashes those inputs into a hex-encoded signature. ``` def verify\_signature(key, input, signature) if signature == create_token(key, input) puts \"Hash values agree -- no tampering occurred." true else puts "Hash values differ! Signed file has been tampered with!" false end end 


/webhooks-validation

webhookExceptions

Webhook exceptions

As with any REST API call, a webhook sent by Roostify returns a success (<b>2xx</b>) or failure status. In most cases of success or failure, Roostify does not resend the webhook; with the following exceptions, in which case Roostify attempts to resend the webhook with an incremental backoff An http server exception occurs during the webhook request. It returns a 200 response with a non-JSONic body containing `ENOENT`. It returns 429 indicating too many requests. It returns 503 indicating the service is unavailable. It returns 504 indicating a gateway timeout. 


/webhooks-success
